Below is a complete, zero-copy (Python-side) pybind11 interface that lets you:

set Runner.jPars_file and Runner.jBlock_file

call Runner.execute() (GIL released)

read all iteration coordinates as a NumPy view (no copy)

read W/H as NumPy views

read all iteration metrics as a NumPy structured array view

read best coords and best metrics

read all optimizer parameters (cheap dict)

To make the views safe + fast, you need a few surgical C++ changes (mainly: make HistoryStore store data in a stable contiguous buffer with getters, and make Metrics a standard-layout struct).

1) Required C++ code changes (exact “replace/insert” pieces)
1.1 Replace your Metrics class with a standard-layout struct

REPLACE the current class Metrics{ ... } with this:

// --- REPLACE ENTIRE Metrics DEFINITION WITH THIS ---
struct Metrics {
  double bbox_area = 0.0;
  double bbox_aspect = 0.0;
  double hpwl = 0.0;
  double overlap = 0.0;
  double boundary_violation = 0.0;
  double aspect_ratio_violation = 0.0;
  double augmented_objective = 0.0;
  double bbox_cx = 0.0, bbox_cy = 0.0, bbox_w = 0.0, bbox_h = 0.0;
  std::size_t iteration_index = 0;
};


Why: pybind11 can expose this as a NumPy structured dtype with zero-copy.

1.2 Replace HistoryStore with a pre-sized, stable-buffer version + getters

This prevents reallocation invalidating pointers and enables very fast views.

REPLACE your entire HistoryStore class with:

// --- REPLACE ENTIRE HistoryStore DEFINITION WITH THIS ---
class HistoryStore {
public:
  HistoryStore() = default;

  // reserve_iters should be (max_iter + 1) typically
  void init(std::size_t n, std::size_t reserve_iters) {
    n_ = n;
    max_iters_ = std::max<std::size_t>(1, reserve_iters);

    iter_count_ = 0;
    best_index_ = 0;
    best_obj_ = std::numeric_limits<double>::infinity();
    best_metrics_ = Metrics{};

    // Pre-size so memory is stable and "elements exist" (safe to view from Python)
    coords_.assign(max_iters_ * 2 * n_, 0.0);
    iter_metrics_.assign(max_iters_, Metrics{});
    best_coords_.assign(2 * n_, 0.0);
  }

  void reset_runtime_only() {
    iter_count_ = 0;
    best_index_ = 0;
    best_obj_ = std::numeric_limits<double>::infinity();
    best_metrics_ = Metrics{};
    std::fill(coords_.begin(), coords_.end(), 0.0);
    std::fill(iter_metrics_.begin(), iter_metrics_.end(), Metrics{});
    std::fill(best_coords_.begin(), best_coords_.end(), 0.0);
  }

  void push(const arma::mat& x, const Metrics& m) {
    if (iter_count_ >= max_iters_) return; // safety; shouldn't happen if sized correctly

    const double* p = x.memptr();
    const std::size_t off = iter_count_ * (2 * n_);

    // Copy into our stable buffer (this is internal storage, not Python-side copying)
    std::copy(p, p + (2 * n_), coords_.begin() + static_cast<std::ptrdiff_t>(off));

    iter_metrics_[iter_count_] = m;

    if (m.augmented_objective < best_obj_) {
      best_obj_ = m.augmented_objective;
      best_index_ = iter_count_;
      best_metrics_ = m;
      std::copy(p, p + (2 * n_), best_coords_.begin());
    }

    ++iter_count_;
  }

  // ---- getters for pybind zero-copy views ----
  std::size_t n() const noexcept { return n_; }
  std::size_t max_iters() const noexcept { return max_iters_; }
  std::size_t iterations() const noexcept { return iter_count_; }
  std::size_t best_index() const noexcept { return best_index_; }

  const std::vector<double>& coords_buffer() const noexcept { return coords_; }        // size = max_iters * 2n
  const std::vector<double>& best_coords() const noexcept { return best_coords_; }    // size = 2n
  const std::vector<Metrics>& metrics_buffer() const noexcept { return iter_metrics_; } // size = max_iters
  const Metrics& best_metrics() const noexcept { return best_metrics_; }

private:
  std::size_t n_ = 0;
  std::size_t max_iters_ = 0;
  std::size_t iter_count_ = 0;

  std::vector<double> coords_;       // [iter][2n] flattened
  std::vector<Metrics> iter_metrics_;

  std::size_t best_index_ = 0;
  double best_obj_ = std::numeric_limits<double>::infinity();
  std::vector<double> best_coords_;
  Metrics best_metrics_;
};

1.3 Placement: add read-only accessors needed by Runner (and init store with max_iter+1)

You said only HistoryStore and Runner have .cpp; Placement is header-only. Add these methods.

INSERT inside class Placement public: section:

// --- INSERT INSIDE Placement public: ---
const HistoryStore& history() const noexcept { return store_; }
HistoryStore& history() noexcept { return store_; }

const LayoutEvaluator& evaluator() const noexcept { return evaluator_; }
const LayoutConfig& config() const noexcept { return cfg_; }

bool optimized() const noexcept { return optimized_; }
double runtime_seconds() const noexcept { return runtime_s_; }


Then CHANGE your load() so it sizes the store with (max_iter + 1):

REPLACE the tail of Placement::load(...) that currently does:

evaluator_.init(cfg_, store_);
store_.init(cfg_.blocks.size());


with:

evaluator_.init(cfg_, store_);
store_.init(cfg_.blocks.size(), cfg_.optimizer.max_iter + 1);

1.4 Runner: add setters/getters + forwarding access (still “Runner-only” for Python)

In Runner header, INSERT into public::

// --- INSERT INSIDE Runner public: ---
void set_jPars_file(const std::string& p) { jPars_file = p; }
void set_jBlock_file(const std::string& p) { jBlock_file = p; }
const std::string& get_jPars_file() const noexcept { return jPars_file; }
const std::string& get_jBlock_file() const noexcept { return jBlock_file; }

const Placement& placement() const noexcept { return place; }
Placement& placement() noexcept { return place; }


If you already have plptr() it’s fine; keep it. The above just standardizes.

1.5 CMakeLists.txt: fix a typo (your snippet has pydin11)

REPLACE:

COMMAND "${Python3_EXECUTABLE}" -m pydin11 --cmakedir


with:

COMMAND "${Python3_EXECUTABLE}" -m pybind11 --cmakedir

2) Complete src/pybind_module.cpp (drop-in)

Save this as: src/pybind_module.cpp

#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/numpy.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>

#include <cstddef>
#include <cstdint>
#include <vector>
#include <string>

// Include ONLY your top-level Runner header; it should pull needed types transitively.
#include "runner.hpp"

namespace py = pybind11;

// Register Metrics as a NumPy structured dtype (zero-copy structured array view).
// This requires Metrics to be a standard-layout struct with PUBLIC fields.
PYBIND11_NUMPY_DTYPE(Metrics,
  bbox_area,
  bbox_aspect,
  hpwl,
  overlap,
  boundary_violation,
  aspect_ratio_violation,
  augmented_objective,
  bbox_cx, bbox_cy, bbox_w, bbox_h,
  iteration_index
);

// Helper: create a zero-copy NumPy array view over a raw pointer.
// base: keeps C++ owner alive (we use the Runner instance).
static py::array make_array_view_double(
    const py::object& base,
    double* ptr,
    const std::vector<py::ssize_t>& shape,
    const std::vector<py::ssize_t>& strides)
{
  py::buffer_info info(
      ptr,
      sizeof(double),
      py::format_descriptor<double>::format(),
      static_cast<py::ssize_t>(shape.size()),
      shape,
      strides
  );
  return py::array(info, base);
}

static py::array make_array_view_metrics(
    const py::object& base,
    Metrics* ptr,
    py::ssize_t n)
{
  // 1D structured array: shape (n,), stride sizeof(Metrics)
  py::buffer_info info(
      ptr,
      sizeof(Metrics),
      py::format_descriptor<Metrics>::format(),
      1,
      std::vector<py::ssize_t>{n},
      std::vector<py::ssize_t>{static_cast<py::ssize_t>(sizeof(Metrics))}
  );
  return py::array(py::dtype::of<Metrics>(), info, base);
}

PYBIND11_MODULE(placement_engine_py, m) {
  m.doc() = "Rectangle placement engine bindings (zero-copy views for history/metrics).";

  py::class_<Runner>(m, "Runner")
    .def(py::init<>())

    // File paths
    .def_property("jPars_file",
      [](const Runner& r) { return r.get_jPars_file(); },
      [](Runner& r, const std::string& p) { r.set_jPars_file(p); }
    )
    .def_property("jBlock_file",
      [](const Runner& r) { return r.get_jBlock_file(); },
      [](Runner& r, const std::string& p) { r.set_jBlock_file(p); }
    )

    // Execute optimizer (release GIL)
    .def("execute",
      [](Runner& r) {
        py::gil_scoped_release release;
        r.execute();
      },
      "Run the optimizer (GIL released)."
    )

    // Basic counters
    .def("num_blocks",
      [](const Runner& r) -> std::size_t {
        return r.placement().history().n();
      }
    )
    .def("max_iters_reserved",
      [](const Runner& r) -> std::size_t {
        return r.placement().history().max_iters();
      }
    )
    .def("iterations",
      [](const Runner& r) -> std::size_t {
        return r.placement().history().iterations();
      }
    )
    .def("best_index",
      [](const Runner& r) -> std::size_t {
        return r.placement().history().best_index();
      }
    )

    // ---- Zero-copy views ----

    // coords_history(): shape = (iters, n, 2), view into HistoryStore::coords_buffer()
    .def("coords_history",
      [](Runner& r) -> py::array {
        auto base = py::cast(&r); // keep Runner alive

        const HistoryStore& hs = r.placement().history();
        const std::size_t n = hs.n();
        const std::size_t iters = hs.iterations();

        const auto& buf = hs.coords_buffer();
        double* ptr = const_cast<double*>(buf.data()); // view only; Python should not mutate

        // layout: [iter][2n] flattened -> reshape (iter, n, 2)
        const py::ssize_t S0 = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(iters);
        const py::ssize_t S1 = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(n);
        const py::ssize_t S2 = 2;

        const py::ssize_t stride_iter = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(2 * n * sizeof(double));
        const py::ssize_t stride_n    = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(2 * sizeof(double));
        const py::ssize_t stride_xy   = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(sizeof(double));

        return make_array_view_double(
          base, ptr,
          {S0, S1, S2},
          {stride_iter, stride_n, stride_xy}
        );
      },
      "Zero-copy view of all iteration coordinates as (iters, n, 2)."
    )

    // coords_at(i): shape = (n,2) view into buffer at iteration i
    .def("coords_at",
      [](Runner& r, std::size_t i) -> py::array {
        auto base = py::cast(&r);

        const HistoryStore& hs = r.placement().history();
        const std::size_t n = hs.n();
        const std::size_t iters = hs.iterations();
        if (i >= iters) throw py::index_error("coords_at: iteration out of range");

        const auto& buf = hs.coords_buffer();
        double* ptr0 = const_cast<double*>(buf.data());
        double* ptr = ptr0 + static_cast<std::ptrdiff_t>(i * 2 * n);

        const py::ssize_t S0 = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(n);
        const py::ssize_t S1 = 2;

        const py::ssize_t stride_n  = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(2 * sizeof(double));
        const py::ssize_t stride_xy = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(sizeof(double));

        return make_array_view_double(base, ptr, {S0, S1}, {stride_n, stride_xy});
      },
      py::arg("i"),
      "Zero-copy view of coordinates at iteration i as (n,2)."
    )

    // best_coords(): shape = (n,2)
    .def("best_coords",
      [](Runner& r) -> py::array {
        auto base = py::cast(&r);

        const HistoryStore& hs = r.placement().history();
        const std::size_t n = hs.n();

        const auto& buf = hs.best_coords();
        double* ptr = const_cast<double*>(buf.data());

        const py::ssize_t S0 = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(n);
        const py::ssize_t S1 = 2;

        const py::ssize_t stride_n  = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(2 * sizeof(double));
        const py::ssize_t stride_xy = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(sizeof(double));

        return make_array_view_double(base, ptr, {S0, S1}, {stride_n, stride_xy});
      },
      "Zero-copy view of best coordinates as (n,2)."
    )

    // widths(): shape = (n,)
    .def("widths",
      [](Runner& r) -> py::array {
        auto base = py::cast(&r);

        const auto& w = r.placement().evaluator().WVec();
        double* ptr = const_cast<double*>(w.data());
        const py::ssize_t n = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(w.size());

        return make_array_view_double(
          base, ptr,
          {n},
          {static_cast<py::ssize_t>(sizeof(double))}
        );
      },
      "Zero-copy view of widths (n,)."
    )

    // heights(): shape = (n,)
    .def("heights",
      [](Runner& r) -> py::array {
        auto base = py::cast(&r);

        const auto& h = r.placement().evaluator().HVec();
        double* ptr = const_cast<double*>(h.data());
        const py::ssize_t n = static_cast<py::ssize_t>(h.size());

        return make_array_view_double(
          base, ptr,
          {n},
          {static_cast<py::ssize_t>(sizeof(double))}
        );
      },
      "Zero-copy view of heights (n,)."
    )

    // metrics_history(): structured array shape = (iters,)
    .def("metrics_history",
      [](Runner& r) -> py::array {
        auto base = py::cast(&r);

        const HistoryStore& hs = r.placement().history();
        const std::size_t iters = hs.iterations();

        const auto& buf = hs.metrics_buffer();
        Metrics* ptr = const_cast<Metrics*>(buf.data());

        return make_array_view_metrics(base, ptr, static_cast<py::ssize_t>(iters));
      },
      "Zero-copy view of metrics history as a NumPy structured array (iters,)."
    )

    // best_metrics(): return as small dict (cheap)
    .def("best_metrics",
      [](const Runner& r) -> py::dict {
        const Metrics& bm = r.placement().history().best_metrics();
        py::dict d;
        d["iteration_index"] = bm.iteration_index;
        d["bbox_area"] = bm.bbox_area;
        d["bbox_aspect"] = bm.bbox_aspect;
        d["hpwl"] = bm.hpwl;
        d["overlap"] = bm.overlap;
        d["boundary_violation"] = bm.boundary_violation;
        d["aspect_ratio_violation"] = bm.aspect_ratio_violation;
        d["augmented_objective"] = bm.augmented_objective;
        d["bbox_cx"] = bm.bbox_cx;
        d["bbox_cy"] = bm.bbox_cy;
        d["bbox_w"] = bm.bbox_w;
        d["bbox_h"] = bm.bbox_h;
        return d;
      },
      "Best metrics as a dict (tiny, cheap)."
    )

    // optimizer_params(): return dict (small, cheap)
    .def("optimizer_params",
      [](const Runner& r) -> py::dict {
        const auto& opt = r.placement().config().optimizer;
        py::dict d;
        d["algorithm"] = opt.algorithm;
        d["max_iter"] = opt.max_iter;
        d["stopping_criteria"] = opt.stopping_criteria;
        d["stopping_value"] = opt.stopping_value;
        d["seed"] = opt.seed;
        d["pop_size"] = opt.pop_size;
        d["recombination"] = opt.recombination;
        d["strategy"] = opt.strategy;
        d["mutation_min"] = opt.mutation_min;
        d["mutation_max"] = opt.mutation_max;
        return d;
      },
      "All optimizer parameters as dict (small)."
    )
  ;
}


Python-side is zero-copy for:

coords_history(), coords_at(i), best_coords(), widths(), heights(), metrics_history()

(They are views into C++ owned memory. Don’t wrap them in np.array(...) unless you want a copy.)

3) How to use it from Python (+ a small Panel app with slider)
import numpy as np
import panel as pn
from bokeh.plotting import figure
from bokeh.models import ColumnDataSource

import placement_engine_py as pe

pn.extension("bokeh")

runner = pe.Runner()
runner.jPars_file  = r"D:\path\to\params.json"
runner.jBlock_file = r"D:\path\to\blocks.json"

runner.execute()

coords = runner.coords_history()     # (iters, n, 2) zero-copy view
w = runner.widths()                  # (n,) zero-copy view
h = runner.heights()                 # (n,) zero-copy view
metrics = runner.metrics_history()   # (iters,) structured array view

iters = runner.iterations()
n = runner.num_blocks()

# Initial iteration
i0 = 0
source = ColumnDataSource(data=dict(
    x = coords[i0, :, 0],
    y = coords[i0, :, 1],
    w = w,
    h = h,
))

p = figure(title="Placement iterations", match_aspect=True, width=700, height=700)
p.rect(x="x", y="y", width="w", height="h", source=source, fill_alpha=0.35, line_alpha=0.9)

slider = pn.widgets.IntSlider(name="Iteration", start=0, end=max(0, iters-1), value=0)

# Fast update: swap x/y arrays (they are numpy views)
def _on_iter_change(event):
    i = int(event.new)
    source.data.update(
        x = coords[i, :, 0],
        y = coords[i, :, 1],
        w = w,
        h = h,
    )
slider.param.watch(_on_iter_change, "value")

best_idx = runner.best_index()
best_metrics = runner.best_metrics()

info = pn.pane.Markdown(
    f"**iters:** {iters}  \n"
    f"**best_idx:** {best_idx}  \n"
    f"**best_obj:** {best_metrics['augmented_objective']:.6g}"
)

pn.Column(info, slider, p).servable()


Tip for speed: keep coords, w, h cached (as above). Don’t call runner.coords_history() repeatedly inside callbacks.

4) Notes on “ZERO COPYING ACTION” and <10 ms latency

The bindings above guarantee zero-copy for all large arrays when crossing into Python.

Internally, you must store iteration history somewhere; that necessarily involves copying the optimizer’s current x into your history buffer. The approach above makes that one fast contiguous copy per iteration into pre-sized memory (no realloc jitter).

execute() releases the GIL so your Panel server thread won’t freeze while C++ runs.

5) Future-proofing for “multiple PlacementEngine objects per Runner”

If you want one Runner to manage multiple variations (e.g., multiple jBlock_files) concurrently, the clean extension is:

Runner holds std::vector<Placement> engines_;

each engine has its own HistoryStore and LayoutEvaluator

expose Runner.run(index) and Runner.coords_history(index) etc.

The pybind approach stays the same: return NumPy views into the chosen engine’s buffers.







#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/numpy.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>

#include <type_traits>
#include <cstddef>
#include <cstdint>
#include <string>
#include <vector>

// IMPORTANT: include the header that DEFINES Metrics explicitly.
// Do NOT rely on runner.hpp or other headers to include it for you.
#include "data_classes.h"

// Hard compile-time checks: if these fail, Metrics is not visible/complete here.
static_assert(sizeof(Metrics) > 0, "Metrics is not visible or is incomplete at this point.");
static_assert(std::is_standard_layout_v<Metrics>, "Metrics must be standard-layout for PYBIND11_NUMPY_DTYPE.");
static_assert(std::is_trivially_copyable_v<Metrics>, "Metrics must be trivially copyable for zero-copy NumPy views.");

// Must be at *global scope* (not inside PYBIND11_MODULE, not inside any namespace).
PYBIND11_NUMPY_DTYPE(Metrics,
  bbox_area,
  bbox_aspect,
  hpwl,
  overlap,
  boundary_violation,
  aspect_ratio_violation,
  augmented_objective,
  bbox_cx, bbox_cy, bbox_w, bbox_h,
  iteration_index
);

// Now include runner AFTER dtype registration (order is not critical now,
// but this avoids any possibility of a forward declaration shadowing the full type).
#include "runner.hpp"

namespace py = pybind11;
